subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis. No unique autapomorphies. Breast, fins and throat yellowish (vs. greyish or strongly yellow in other species of 
Bussingius
); basal process on the largest first-arch gill-rakers; lower symphysial teeth bicuspidate, with a small lingual cusp (also in 
Cryptoheros septemfasciatus
); distally two rows of interradial scales on anal fin (also in 
Cr. nanoluteus
); spots on opercle, part of a rather indistinct longitudinal stripe.
